{"id":"0809.2625","submitter":"Arne Kovac","authors":"A. Kovac and P.L. Davies","title":"Quantifying the cost of simultaneous non-parametric approximation of\n  several samples","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.ST stat.TH","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider the standard non-parametric regression model with Gaussian errors\nbut where the data consist of different samples. The question to be answered is\nwhether the samples can be adequately represented by the same regression\nfunction. To do this we define for each sample a universal, honest and\nnon-asymptotic confidence region for the regression function. Any subset of the\nsamples can be represented by the same function if and only if the intersection\nof the corresponding confidence regions is non-empty. If the empirical supports\nof the samples are disjoint then the intersection of the confidence regions is\nalways non--empty and a negative answer can only be obtained by placing shape\nor quantitative smoothness conditions on the joint approximation. Alternatively\na simplest joint approximation function can be calculated which gives a measure\nof the cost of the joint approximation, for example, the number of extra peaks\nrequired.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 Sep 2008 22:00:22 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-09-17"}
